<part>Inline features</part>

<p>
You can declare HTML entities by code point (ex: &#8364;), or by name (ex: &euro;).
Another example is &amp;, the &lt;, the &gt;, the &quot;, and &apos;.
</p>

<p>
This is a paragraph with <b>bold text</b>, <i>italic text</i>, and <tt>monospaced text</tt>.
It also contains <caps>text in small caps</caps>, <del>corrected</del><ins>fixed</ins> text, <sup>superscripts</sup>,
and <sub>subscripts</sub>. Also, <mbox><i>all of this emphasised text should appear on the same line.</i></mbox>
</p>

<p>
This paragraph contains an external link to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/">Wikipedia</a>,
and an internal link to Section <ref href="sec:intro"/>, a smarter link to <sref href="sec:intro"/>,
and a manual link <mref href="sec:intro">to that same section</mref>.  Finally, it also contains a note<see href="note"/>
and bibliography references<cite href="kur1"/>.
</p>

<part>Block features</part>

<h1>Unordered lists</h1>

<ul>
	<li>One item</li>
	<li>Another item</li>
	<li>Yet another item</li>
</ul>

<h1>Ordered lists</h1>

<ol>
	<li><p>One item</p></li>
	<li><p>Another item</p></li>
	<li><p>Yet another item</p></li>
</ol>

<h1>Definition lists</h1>

<dl>
	<dt>One item</dt>
	<dd><p>One item description</p></dd>

	<dt>Another item</dt>
	<dd><p>Another item description</p></dd>

	<dt>Yet another item</dt>
	<dd><p>Yet another item description</p></dd>
</dl>

